post_cb({"24074445": {"Id": "24074445", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>It's undefined behavior, so there's no guarantee that it will work.</p>\n<p>When it does work correctly, it's because the result happens to be computed in the same CPU register that is used to return integer values from functions. This is dependent on a many factors (e.g. compiler version, system ABI, compiler options, surrounding code), so you can't rely on it.  </p>\n", "LastActivityDate": "2014-06-06T04:57:22.780", "CommentCount": "0", "CreationDate": "2014-06-06T04:57:22.780", "ParentId": "24074392", "Score": "1", "OwnerUserId": "374746"}, "bq_ids": {"n4140": {"so_24074392_24074411_1": {"length": 9, "quality": 0.9, "section_id": 7149}, "so_24074392_24074411_0": {"length": 12, "quality": 1.0, "section_id": 3913}}, "n3337": {"so_24074392_24074411_1": {"length": 9, "quality": 0.9, "section_id": 6893}, "so_24074392_24074411_0": {"length": 12, "quality": 1.0, "section_id": 3773}}, "n4659": {"so_24074392_24074411_0": {"length": 9, "quality": 0.75, "section_id": 4799}}}, "24074411": {"Id": "24074411", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>Without <code>return</code> statement in function this code invoked <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Undefined_behavior\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\"><strong>undefined behavior</strong></a>. A non <code>void</code> function must have a return statement.   </p>\n<h3>C++11 \u00a7 6.6.3 The return statement:</h3>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_24074392_24074411_0\">3 ...Flowing off the end of a function is equivalent to a return with no value; this results in <strong>undefined behavior</strong> in a value-returning function.   </p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>As <a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/users/1322972/whozcraig\">WhozCraig</a> stated in comment,  there is one standard-defined exception to the non-void return value requiring a <code>return</code>: <code>int main()</code> </p>\n<h3>C++11 \u00a7 3.6.1p5 [basic.start.main]</h3>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_24074392_24074411_1\">If control reaches the end of main without encountering a return statement, the effect is that of executing <code>return 0;</code> </p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>In case of UB you may get either expected or unexpected result.<br>\nThe printed value could be the value stored in the stack.</br></p>\n", "LastEditorUserId": "-1", "LastActivityDate": "2014-06-06T05:32:28.030", "Score": "2", "CreationDate": "2014-06-06T04:53:42.287", "ParentId": "24074392", "CommentCount": "5", "OwnerUserId": "2455888", "LastEditDate": "2017-05-23T12:08:57.180"}, "24074427": {"Id": "24074427", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>It's undefined behavior if a function that returns non-void doesn't return anything. The compiler should give you at least a warning. </p>\n<p>What probably happens is, the value of <code>product</code> is still in the stack after the function exits, and <code>std::cout</code> prints that value. But again, don't rely on undefined behavior.</p>\n", "LastActivityDate": "2014-06-06T04:55:36.223", "CommentCount": "1", "CreationDate": "2014-06-06T04:55:36.223", "ParentId": "24074392", "Score": "1", "OwnerUserId": "1009479"}, "24074392": {"ViewCount": "115", "Body": "<p>i found this code in some site that it doesn't have any return statement for returning the value.\nBut in the site it is written as it gives a compile time error.\nWhile i was trying to compile the program for knowing what the error will be seen in compiler.\nThe program compiled successfully with out giving any error..</p>\n<p>The c++ code is :</p>\n<pre><code>int multiply(int x, int y)\n{\n  int product = x * y;\n}\n\nint main()\n{\n  cout &lt;&lt; multiply(4, 5) &lt;&lt; endl;\n  return 0;\n}\n</code></pre>\n<p>output : 20</p>\n<p>Now I am confused  that without any return statement how the compilation is successful.</p>\n", "Title": "without return statement function executed successfully", "CreationDate": "2014-06-06T04:51:55.067", "Id": "24074392", "CommentCount": "5", "LastEditDate": "2017-01-15T14:40:50.760", "PostTypeId": "1", "LastEditorUserId": "1033581", "LastActivityDate": "2017-01-15T14:40:50.760", "Tags": "<c++>", "Score": "0", "OwnerUserId": "1903535", "ClosedDate": "2014-06-06T04:58:58.260", "AnswerCount": "3"}});